column2: cor_df <-dplyr::select(tiny, ageENG, ethENG, Resilience, SecVic2, SACSEM)
apa.cor.table(cor_df, filename = 'Dissertation Correlation Matrix.doc', table.number = 1, show.conf.interval = TRUE, show.sig.stars = TRUE, landscape = TRUE)
Means, standard deviations, and correlations with confidence intervals

Note. M and SD are used to represent mean and standard deviation, respectively.
Values in square brackets indicate the 95% confidence interval.
The confidence interval is a plausible range of population correlations 
that could have caused the sample correlation (Cumming, 2014).
 * indicates p < .05. ** indicates p < .01.
